'''Elizabeth Ivy Wagmeister''' (born July 20, 1990{{efn|name=Birth date note}}) is an American journalist, reporter and writer. She is the senior correspondent at ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', and co-host of Fox's nationally syndicated entertainment news show "Page Six TV." She was named onto Forbes 30 Under 30 list for 2019.<ref>https://www.forbes.com/profile/elizabeth-wagmeister/?list=30under30-media#4f91b2cf34c0</ref>

==Early life and education==
Wagmeister was born and raised in the Los Angeles area. She attended [[Calabasas High School]], and graduated from the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]] in 2012 with a bachelor's degree in communication and dual minors in multimedia writing and art history. She wrote for the school newspaper ''[[The Daily Nexus]]'', and was vice president of the [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]] sorority.

In 2009, she became one of the original ten founding collegiate members of [[Her Campus]]{{r|Mulvey (2013)}} and worked for the online magazine until her graduation, launching a culinary blog "Elizabeth's Eats," and winning a national award.{{specify|date=June 2016}} In 2010, Wagmeister was a news intern for Los Angeles morning show ''[[Good Day L.A.]]'' Later, she interned at ''Santa Barbara Magazine'', and was published in ''[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]'' magazine. In 2011, Wagmeister was one of 25 students, and the only representative of California, to be selected nationally for the Associated Society of Magazine Editors internship program, which brought her to New York City to intern at ''[[TV Guide]]''.

==Career==
Wagmeister was offered a job as the assistant to the editor in-chief of ''TV Guide'' and moved to New York City where she rose the ranks as a red carpet reporter and writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/authors/elizabeth-wagmeister/|title=Elizabeth Wagmeister|work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref>

In 2014, at 23 years old, [[Bonnie Fuller]] hired her as the senior entertainment editor of [[HollywoodLife]] where she ran the gossip site's television and film verticals, and hosted the brand’s daily YouTube series with her videos bringing in over 30 million views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/author/elizabeth-wagmeister/|title=Elizabeth Wagmeister|work=[[HollywoodLife]]}}</ref>

Wagmeister was hired by ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' in late 2014 to become the trade magazine's Los Angeles-based TV reporter. She is an on-camera host for the digital "Variety Artisans" series, "Variety Contenders" award season interview series and "Variety On Delta" in-flight entertainment.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/elizabeth-wagmeister-joins-variety-as-tv-reporter-1201379982/|title=Elizabeth Wagmeister Joins Variety as TV Reporter|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 16, 2014}}</ref>

She frequently appears on local, national and digital news, including [[Entertainment Tonight]], [[Access Hollywood]], [[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]], [[Good Morning America]], [[CBS This Morning]], [[The Wendy Williams Show]], [[The Talk (talk show)|The Talk]], and is a regular guest contributor on FOX 11 News in Los Angeles. She has been featured as an entertainment expert on [[NPR]] and Sirius XM, and has moderated panels for shows including "Modern Family" and [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]]'s ''[[UnReal]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!-- Staff writers; no by-line. --> |title='UnReal' Co-Creator Knows How Series Will End, Targeting Five Seasons |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url=https://variety.com/2016/scene/news/unreal-ending-five-seasons-sarah-gertrude-shapiro-lifetime-1201788993/ |access-date=July 7, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, she began a weekly entertainment segment on ''Good Day L.A.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxla.com/good-day/good-day-la-experts-and-other-guests/36474729-story|title=Elizabeth Wagmeister from Variety with 'Empire' Exclusives|work=[[KTTV]]|last1=Pulfrey|first1=Michelle|last2=DeSocio|first2=Jeffrey Thomas|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref>

In July 2016, she was named a co-host on Fox's daily entertainment news show "Page Six TV," which films in New York City.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!-- Staff writers; no by-line. --> |title=Variety's Elizabeth Wagmeister Named Contributor to 'Page Six TV' |date=July 6, 2016 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/page-six-tv-fox-elizabeth-wagmeister-contributor-john-fugelsang-host-1201809178/ |access-date=July 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=<!-- Staff writers; no by-line. --> |title=John Fugelsang, Mario Cantone, Bevy Smith Join 'Page Six TV' |date=July 6, 2016 |work=Page Six |url=http://pagesix.com/2016/07/06/john-fugelsang-mario-cantone-bevy-smith-join-page-six-tv/ |access-date=July 7, 2016}}</ref> The series launched into national syndication in September 2017 and was renewed for a second season in 2018. She was named onto Forbes 30 Under 30 list in the media category for 2019.

